“No one will ever know the violence it took to become this gentle”

At almost 34 years old I’ve spent my whole adult life in this industry. At 19 I was issued a M4 in infantry school and was told “this is what you kill your enemy with”. All we were told was “kill”. I went to airborne school and was told “when you jump out of this plane, be ready to kill the enemy”. Deployments later on only exposed me to what true acts of violence are.

After exiting the military I joined the police department in hopes of finding a new passion. I quickly learned working my first year on nights, that almost every night was a fight for your life. Peace did not exist because people only call for help in the chaos.

Fighting for your life nightly, in America, only a few miles from your home and in a country/community you swore to protect. After making the Swat team and Gang unit I realized violence will find me wherever I go, I just have to be more violent then the person trying to kill me. Even off duty and the places we would go in the city I would remember saying “a guy was shot and kill there last week”, “that kangaroo just got robbed”, “a lady was stabbed to death in that house”. Even pumping gas you stayed on high alert because you know the chances of a gun fight from a robbery was high. I could never turned the violence off because the new war zone was home.

I will choose peace over violence, because I know the cost of violence. Deep down the violence is still in me and I will sacrifice. Let a peaceful man be.

Some information I would like to share regarding law enforcement that I wish I'd known.

It is crucial to prioritize personal time and not sacrifice important occasions like birthdays or holidays for overtime or off-duty work.

It is important to understand that individuals outside of your unit do not have a vested interest in the number of  foot/vehicle pursuits, shootings, fights or firearms you have seized. It is essential to prioritize your well-being and return home.

Your department will value your contributions until they no longer require your services. Unfortunately, regardless of the positive impact you may have, even the smallest mistake will overshadow your achievements and result in disciplinary action.

Please remember that you are replaceable. In the unfortunate event of your passing, there will be a brief period of commendation, a memorial service, but your position will likely be filled before the flowers have wilted.

Allocate quality time to spend with your family. Offer them the same dedication and enthusiasm you display when dealing with drug dealers and gang members.

If you find yourself grappling with post-traumatic stress disorder (PTSD), it is highly recommended to seek professional assistance. Do not suppress your emotions, as doing so may lead you into a dark, isolating place burdened with a heavy weight.

Above all, do something today that will keep you alive tomorrow.🏴🏴
